{"id": "c15bc1e5c9ed48399cd58ca96c73d10f", "timestamp": "2025-12-11 08:04:25", "name": "Scientist0", "content": "[retrieved]:", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[95mScientist0\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "574a6193b5b645229be61e8fe92f750f", "timestamp": "2025-12-11 08:04:37", "name": "Scientist0", "content": "This is a compelling direction to explore—especially given the growing need for models that can generalize effectively in low-data regimes while maintaining robustness and interpretability. Building on our team’s strengths in interpretable AI and few-shot learning, I believe we can make a significant contribution by investigating how *semi-factual data*, grounded in human-identified rationales, can be leveraged to improve model generalization with minimal manual overhead.\n\nHere’s what I’m thinking: In few-shot learning, models often fail not because they can’t learn the task, but because they latch onto spurious correlations or surface-level patterns in the limited training data. Human-annotated rationales—such as highlighted evidence spans in text or justifications for labels—offer insight into *why* a label is correct. But manually generating counterfactuals or alternative factual scenarios based on these rationales is expensive.\n\nWhat if, instead, we use those human rationales to *automatically generate semi-factual instances*—plausible variations of input data where the label remains the same despite changes to non-critical features? For example, in a sentiment classification task, if the rationale highlights “best movie ever” as justification for positive sentiment, we could perturb other parts of the sentence (e.g., changing “I watched it last night” to “I saw it years ago”) while preserving the core rationale. The model learns that the label persists across such variations, reinforcing robustness to irrelevant changes.\n\nThe innovation lies in using human rationales not just for explanation or supervision, but as *generative constraints* for data augmentation. This reduces the need for extensive manual intervention because we’re automating the generation process guided by sparse, high-quality human insights. Moreover, since the generated examples are semi-factual (label-preserving), they avoid the pitfalls of fully synthetic counterfactuals that may introduce noise or implausible inputs.\n\nWe could evaluate this approach across NLP and vision domains—e.g., modifying image backgrounds while preserving object-relevant features identified in textual rationales—and measure improvements in out-of-distribution robustness, calibration, and generalization under extreme few-shot conditions.\n\nOne challenge will be ensuring fidelity: how do we validate that the perturbations stay within semantically valid bounds without further human input? Perhaps we can use confidence-aware generation or self-consistency checks via auxiliary models.\n\nWhat do you think? Could this bridge the gap between human interpretability and scalable robustness engineering in low-resource settings?", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[95mScientist0\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "623a02f031b1455b8186f90863de35ed", "timestamp": "2025-12-11 08:04:42", "name": "Scientist0", "content": "The scientist proposes leveraging human-annotated rationales to automatically generate *semi-factual data*—plausible, label-preserving variations of inputs—for improving model generalization in few-shot learning. By using rationales as generative constraints, the approach enables targeted data augmentation that strengthens model robustness to irrelevant changes without requiring extensive manual effort. The method aims to prevent spurious correlations by focusing perturbations on non-critical features while preserving core evidence, and it can be applied across modalities like NLP and vision. Key benefits include reduced manual overhead, improved out-of-distribution robustness, and better calibration. A main challenge is ensuring semantic validity of generated instances, potentially addressed through confidence-aware generation or self-consistency checks with auxiliary models. This strategy seeks to bridge interpretable AI and scalable robustness in low-data settings.", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[95mScientist0\u001b[0m"}
